---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout title="SimDec — Simulation Decomposition">
  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="margin-bottom: 2.75rem;">
    <h1 style="font-size: 2.6rem; margin: 0 0 0.75rem 0;">
      Simulation Decomposition (SimDec)
    </h1>
    <p style="font-size: 1.2rem; opacity: 0.85; margin: 0;">
      A method for turning complex simulation outputs into structured, decision-relevant insight.
    </p>
  </section>

      <!-- WHAT IS -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>What is SimDec?</h2>

        <div style="display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: flex-start; flex-wrap: wrap;">

          <div style="flex: 1 1 520px; min-width: 320px;">
            <p>
              SimDec takes a Monte Carlo simulation dataset, detects which inputs are most influential for the output, and then decomposes the output
              distribution into portions produced by the combinations of these influential inputs.
            </p>

            <p>
              You don’t just learn <em>what</em> factors matter; you see
              <em>how</em> they matter, or <em>how to steer your output</em> to a desired range by
              using these drivers.
            </p>
          </div>

          <aside style="flex: 0 1 420px; min-width: 300px;">
            <a href="/process.PNG" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" style="display: block;">
              <img
                src="/process.PNG"
                alt="SimDec process"
                style="width: 100%; height: auto; border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,.12); border-radius: 12px; cursor: zoom-in;"
              />
            </a>
          </aside>

        </div>
      </section>

      <!-- HOW TO USE -->
      <section style="margin-bottom: 3rem;">
        <h2>How to use SimDec?</h2>

        <p>
          SimDec is an open-source project with several free tools:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            No-code web dashboard
            <a href="https://simdec.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              simdec.io
            </a>.
            Watch
            <a href="https://youtu.be/z0QX121o50A?si=aBGrxJKLN6TmO4sb" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              tutorial
            </a>.
          </li>

          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/Simulation-Decomposition/simdec-python" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              SimDec package in Python
            </a>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/Simulation-Decomposition/simdec-R" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              SimDec package in R
            </a>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/Simulation-Decomposition/simdec-matlab" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              SimDec package for Matlab
            </a>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a href="https://github.com/Simulation-Decomposition/SimulationDecomposition.jl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              SimDec package in Julia
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <p style="margin-top: 1.25rem;">
          Also see:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <a href="https://youtu.be/k0uvq-_zW18?si=mXsL-Xz24yoyN2Kd" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              A quick Monte Carlo simulation in Excel with Data Tables
            </a>
          </li>

          <li>
            <a href="https://youtu.be/bV3X_MSJmYA?si=MqxAY8XJP8W-TyzQ" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
              How to read SimDec
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>

        <figure style="margin: 2rem 0 0 0;">
          <a href="https://simdec.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" title="Try dashboard" style="display: block;">
            <img
              src="/dashboard.JPG"
              alt="SimDec dashboard"
              style="width: 100%; height: auto; border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,.12); border-radius: 12px; cursor: pointer;"
            />
          </a>
        </figure>
      </section>

  <!-- BORN FROM SCIENCE -->
  <section style="margin-bottom: 1rem;">
    <h2>Born from science</h2>

    <div style="display: flex; gap: 1.5rem; align-items: flex-start; flex-wrap: wrap;">
      <div style="flex: 1 1 520px; min-width: 320px;">
        <p>
          SimDec is a set of interdisciplinary inventions: an efficient global sensitivity analysis method
          paired with a decomposition algorithm for visualization. Our SimDec book:
        </p>

        <h3 style="margin-top: 1.25rem; margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
          Sensitivity Analysis for Business, Technology, and Policymaking, Made Easy with Simulation Decomposition (SimDec)
        </h3>

        <ul>
          <li>Foreword by Andrea Saltelli &amp; Afterword by Sam Savage</li>
          <li>Chapter 1: Overview of sensitivity and uncertainty analysis methods</li>
          <li>Chapter 2: Interpretation and usage instructions for SimDec</li>
          <li>Chapter 3: Overview of applications</li>
          <li>Chapters 4-13: Multiple application cases of SimDec</li>
        </ul>

        <p>
          <a
            href="https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/oa-edit/10.4324/9781003453789/sensitivity-analysis-business-technology-policymaking-mariia-kozlova-julian-scott-yeomans"
            target="_blank"
            rel="noopener noreferrer"
          >
            Open access
          </a>
        </p>
      </div>

      <aside style="flex: 0 1 220px; min-width: 200px;">
        <a
          href="https://www.taylorfrancis.com/books/oa-edit/10.4324/9781003453789/sensitivity-analysis-business-technology-policymaking-mariia-kozlova-julian-scott-yeomans"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener noreferrer"
          style="display: block;"
        >
          <img
            src="/book.jpg"
            alt="SimDec book cover"
            style="width: 100%; height: auto; border: 1px solid rgba(0,0,0,.12); border-radius: 12px; cursor: pointer;"
          />
        </a>
      </aside>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>